He has studied the same
charts as the INCA and Philip

00:32:43.400 --> 00:32:47.250 align:middle line:84%
[SPEAKING FRENCH],, those
that show the cases of cancer

00:32:47.250 --> 00:32:50.670 align:middle line:84%
are doubling without the number
of advanced cancers or deaths

00:32:50.670 --> 00:32:52.940 align:middle line:90%
from cancer declining.

00:32:52.940 --> 00:32:55.700 align:middle line:84%
He believes the battle
over the figures is in vain

00:32:55.700 --> 00:32:58.245 align:middle line:84%
and that we are saving women
who don't need to be saved.

00:32:58.245 --> 00:33:01.000 align:middle line:90%


00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:03.790 align:middle line:84%
>> There is an epidemic
of breast cancer.

00:33:03.790 --> 00:33:05.730 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's
secondary to screening.

00:33:05.730 --> 00:33:09.690 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the truth is
that our practices

00:33:09.690 --> 00:33:13.680 align:middle line:84%
as a medical profession can
have tremendous influence

00:33:13.680 --> 00:33:16.630 align:middle line:84%
on the apparent
amount of cancer.

00:33:16.630 --> 00:33:19.620 align:middle line:84%
So ironically, looking
hard for cancer

00:33:19.620 --> 00:33:23.010 align:middle line:84%
is a recipe for a
cancer epidemic.

00:33:23.010 --> 00:33:25.680 align:middle line:84%
And it has allowed us
to sort of understand

00:33:25.680 --> 00:33:28.950 align:middle line:84%
that there's a vast
reservoir of abnormality

00:33:28.950 --> 00:33:31.210 align:middle line:90%
in the human population.

00:33:31.210 --> 00:33:33.600 align:middle line:90%
We just all have abnormalities.

00:33:33.600 --> 00:33:37.110 align:middle line:84%
The breast is a gland,
like the thyroid,

00:33:37.110 --> 00:33:40.520 align:middle line:84%
like the prostate, that is
turning over cells a lot.

00:33:40.520 --> 00:33:42.390 align:middle line:90%
That's what glands do.

00:33:42.390 --> 00:33:46.830 align:middle line:84%
And so their cellular
abnormalities are not rare.

00:33:46.830 --> 00:33:48.000 align:middle line:90%
They're common.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:52.680 align:middle line:84%
But we don't all develop
clinical disease.

00:33:52.680 --> 00:33:56.580 align:middle line:84%
>> Gilbert Welch refers
to the Nielsen study.

00:33:56.580 --> 00:34:00.840 align:middle line:84%
In Copenhagen in the 1980s,
pathologist Maya Nielsen

00:34:00.840 --> 00:34:04.740 align:middle line:84%
had the idea to autopsy the
breasts of around 100 women

00:34:04.740 --> 00:34:07.800 align:middle line:84%
who had not been diagnosed
with breast cancer.

00:34:07.800 --> 00:34:09.360 align:middle line:84%
The only thing
they had in common

00:34:09.360 --> 00:34:11.639 align:middle line:84%
was that they had
all died unexpectedly

00:34:11.639 --> 00:34:13.514 align:middle line:84%
from criminal or
accidental causes.

00:34:13.514 --> 00:34:20.850 align:middle line:90%


00:34:20.850 --> 00:34:23.250 align:middle line:84%
When she examined their
cellular breast tissue

00:34:23.250 --> 00:34:25.320 align:middle line:84%
under the microscope,
she found something

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:26.580 align:middle line:90%
she was not expecting.

00:34:26.580 --> 00:34:30.090 align:middle line:90%


00:34:30.090 --> 00:34:32.610 align:middle line:84%
In her sample of dead
women, the pathologist

00:34:32.610 --> 00:34:34.980 align:middle line:84%
thought she would
discover that 6% of them

00:34:34.980 --> 00:34:38.520 align:middle line:84%
had breast cancer, believed
to be the normal incidence

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:40.780 align:middle line:90%
in the population.

00:34:40.780 --> 00:34:42.510 align:middle line:84%
However, she found
the figure was

00:34:42.510 --> 00:34:48.415 align:middle line:84%
closer to 20%, three
times what she expected.

00:34:48.415 --> 00:34:49.790 align:middle line:84%
This would suggest
that there are

00:34:49.790 --> 00:34:52.340 align:middle line:84%
numerous occurrences
of what we call cancer

00:34:52.340 --> 00:34:54.679 align:middle line:90%
that are never diagnosed.

00:34:54.679 --> 00:34:58.700 align:middle line:84%
Maya Nielsen had just proved the
existence of dormant cancers.

00:34:58.700 --> 00:35:01.610 align:middle line:90%


00:35:01.610 --> 00:35:05.650 align:middle line:84%
>> If we start looking for
early forms of disease,

00:35:05.650 --> 00:35:08.150 align:middle line:84%
one of the things we need to
understand is we're going to be

00:35:08.150 --> 00:35:13.010 align:middle line:84%
treating people who have
these indolent cancers.

00:35:13.010 --> 00:35:15.470 align:middle line:84%
They meet the pathologic
definition of cancer.

00:35:15.470 --> 00:35:17.600 align:middle line:90%
But they're not going anywhere.

00:35:17.600 --> 00:35:18.650 align:middle line:90%
And we'll treat them.

00:35:18.650 --> 00:35:21.230 align:middle line:90%


00:35:21.230 --> 00:35:24.350 align:middle line:84%
>> Every week Gilbert Welch
warns his students about this

00:35:24.350 --> 00:35:27.890 align:middle line:84%
screening that mainly
reveals dormant cancers.

00:35:27.890 --> 00:35:31.370 align:middle line:84%
The phenomenon involves
precancerous lesions, but also

00:35:31.370 --> 00:35:33.320 align:middle line:90%
invasive cancers, too.

00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:36.710 align:middle line:90%
He calls this overdiagnosis.

00:35:36.710 --> 00:35:40.070 align:middle line:84%
>> My major interest in cancer
screening is to tell people

00:35:40.070 --> 00:35:43.220 align:middle line:84%
both sides of the story and
let them make a choice so they

00:35:43.220 --> 00:35:46.400 align:middle line:84%
understand the benefits
and the harms of the deal.

00:35:46.400 --> 00:35:50.570 align:middle line:84%
>> Usually, at least in my
own personal experience,

00:35:50.570 --> 00:35:54.470 align:middle line:84%
I assume in many others, most
people would want to get rid

00:35:54.470 --> 00:35:56.900 align:middle line:84%
of the problem as
quickly as possible.

00:35:56.900 --> 00:36:01.040 align:middle line:84%
>> Question is, if becoming
a case becomes evidence

00:36:01.040 --> 00:36:08.375 align:middle line:84%
of the usefulness of the effort,
it's a recipe for more cases.

00:36:08.375 --> 00:36:11.840 align:middle line:90%


00:36:11.840 --> 00:36:16.730 align:middle line:84%
My best estimate is
somewhere between a third

00:36:16.730 --> 00:36:20.420 align:middle line:84%
and a half of mammagraphically
detected cancers,

00:36:20.420 --> 00:36:24.380 align:middle line:84%
and that includes DCIS,
represent overdiagnosis.

00:36:24.380 --> 00:36:27.080 align:middle line:90%
I know that sounds like a lot.

00:36:27.080 --> 00:36:30.740 align:middle line:84%
But this is the basic
truth about screening.

00:36:30.740 --> 00:36:35.210 align:middle line:84%
You have to involve literally
thousands to help a few.

00:36:35.210 --> 00:36:38.000 align:middle line:84%
And one of the questions
I've been raising

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.640 align:middle line:84%
is that if you have
a situation where

00:36:40.640 --> 00:36:42.710 align:middle line:84%
you have to involve
1,000 people,

00:36:42.710 --> 00:36:47.720 align:middle line:84%
potentially, to help one,
what happens to the other 999?

00:36:47.720 --> 00:36:51.590 align:middle line:84%
And that's an important thing
for health care to be aware of.

00:36:51.590 --> 00:36:56.550 align:middle line:84%
What happens to all
the rest of them?

00:36:56.550 --> 00:36:59.700 align:middle line:84%
>> In Paris, after
42 years in practice,

00:36:59.700 --> 00:37:02.730 align:middle line:84%
radiologist [SPEAKING FRENCH]
has reached the same

00:37:02.730 --> 00:37:04.530 align:middle line:90%
conclusions.

00:37:04.530 --> 00:37:06.810 align:middle line:84%
Yet in the 1980s,
he was involved

00:37:06.810 --> 00:37:09.030 align:middle line:84%
in the introduction of the
breast cancer screening

00:37:09.030 --> 00:37:12.200 align:middle line:90%
program in France.

00:37:12.200 --> 00:37:13.695 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:37:13.695 --> 00:37:15.070 align:middle line:84%
>>INTERPRETER: In
the early '70s,

00:37:15.070 --> 00:37:16.840 align:middle line:84%
we thought the
development of a tumor

00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:20.740 align:middle line:84%
was linear over time,
that it was proportional

00:37:20.740 --> 00:37:22.370 align:middle line:90%
to the passing of time.

00:37:22.370 --> 00:37:24.300 align:middle line:90%
When it's small, it's early.

00:37:24.300 --> 00:37:26.530 align:middle line:90%
When it's big, it's advanced.

00:37:26.530 --> 00:37:28.180 align:middle line:84%
We thought that
mammograms allowed

00:37:28.180 --> 00:37:31.210 align:middle line:84%
us to make a diagnose before
the tumor was palpable.

00:37:31.210 --> 00:37:34.630 align:middle line:84%
Back then, we thought we'd
diagnose all the tumors,

00:37:34.630 --> 00:37:37.070 align:middle line:84%
and then treat them
as early as possible.

00:37:37.070 --> 00:37:39.245 align:middle line:84%
And as a result, we'd
solved the problem.

00:37:39.245 --> 00:37:44.110 align:middle line:90%


00:37:44.110 --> 00:37:47.050 align:middle line:84%
>> But in practice, he realized
that cancers do not all grow

00:37:47.050 --> 00:37:48.430 align:middle line:90%
in a linear fashion.

00:37:48.430 --> 00:37:51.310 align:middle line:84%
Some grow very quickly,
and others take more time

00:37:51.310 --> 00:37:53.620 align:middle line:90%
or even disappear altogether.

00:37:53.620 --> 00:37:56.880 align:middle line:84%
That throws into question the
relevance of early detection.

00:37:56.880 --> 00:37:59.650 align:middle line:84%
[SPEAKING FRENCH] now
refuses to carry it out.

00:37:59.650 --> 00:38:01.510 align:middle line:84%
He has closed his
independent practice

00:38:01.510 --> 00:38:04.820 align:middle line:84%
and is now looking into our
understanding of cancer.

00:38:04.820 --> 00:38:05.752 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:38:05.752 --> 00:38:07.210 align:middle line:84%
>>INTERPRETER: In
the beginning, we

00:38:07.210 --> 00:38:10.720 align:middle line:84%
might have thought that this
overdiagnosis was marginal.

00:38:10.720 --> 00:38:12.640 align:middle line:90%
But it ended up being huge.

00:38:12.640 --> 00:38:15.400 align:middle line:84%
Moreover, it begs the
question as to why

00:38:15.400 --> 00:38:18.460 align:middle line:84%
there are some cancers that
just keep on getting worse

00:38:18.460 --> 00:38:22.285 align:middle line:84%
until the person dies and
others that just don't evolve.

00:38:22.285 --> 00:38:25.370 align:middle line:90%


00:38:25.370 --> 00:38:27.970 align:middle line:84%
Today, we don't know how
to tell the difference

00:38:27.970 --> 00:38:33.130 align:middle line:84%
between an overdiagnosed cancer
and a progressive cancer.

00:38:33.130 --> 00:38:34.780 align:middle line:90%
And this raises a question.

00:38:34.780 --> 00:38:36.790 align:middle line:84%
At which point are
we really sick?

00:38:36.790 --> 00:38:41.920 align:middle line:90%


00:38:41.920 --> 00:38:45.340 align:middle line:84%
>> The answer given today is to
diagnose as early as possible

00:38:45.340 --> 00:38:47.740 align:middle line:84%
and to treat
precancers and cancers,

00:38:47.740 --> 00:38:50.320 align:middle line:84%
assuming that they will each
evolve into a terminal disease.

00:38:50.320 --> 00:38:59.751 align:middle line:90%


00:38:59.751 --> 00:39:01.670 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:39:01.670 --> 00:39:03.885 align:middle line:84%
The day of Monique's
surgery has arrived.

00:39:03.885 --> 00:39:13.006 align:middle line:90%


00:39:13.006 --> 00:39:14.480 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:39:14.480 --> 00:39:16.980 align:middle line:84%
>>INTERPRETER: Monique
has a high grade DCIS.

00:39:16.980 --> 00:39:21.850 align:middle line:84%
It's considered to be the stage
just before invasive cancer.

00:39:21.850 --> 00:39:25.830 align:middle line:84%
So the screening process
has done its job.

00:39:25.830 --> 00:39:28.930 align:middle line:84%
By revealing these
legions at this stage,

00:39:28.930 --> 00:39:31.740 align:middle line:84%
they can be operated
in good conditions.

00:39:31.740 --> 00:39:34.631 align:middle line:84%
And the treatments will
be extremely effective.

00:39:34.631 --> 00:39:39.710 align:middle line:90%


00:39:39.710 --> 00:39:43.310 align:middle line:84%
>> The surgery lasts for one
hour under general anesthetic.

00:39:43.310 --> 00:39:45.065 align:middle line:84%
Monique will go home
that same evening.

00:39:45.065 --> 00:39:47.600 align:middle line:90%


00:39:47.600 --> 00:39:52.400 align:middle line:84%
The surgeon, [SPEAKING FRENCH],,
carries out 250 such operations

00:39:52.400 --> 00:39:53.200 align:middle line:90%
every year.

00:39:53.200 --> 00:39:56.310 align:middle line:90%


00:39:56.310 --> 00:39:58.035 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:39:58.035 --> 00:39:59.660 align:middle line:84%
>>INTERPRETER: We
know that we probably

00:39:59.660 --> 00:40:04.040 align:middle line:84%
overtreat a certain number of
patients who have abnormalities

00:40:04.040 --> 00:40:06.500 align:middle line:84%
that won't grow
very much and which

00:40:06.500 --> 00:40:10.010 align:middle line:84%
probably wouldn't be responsible
for the death of that person.

00:40:10.010 --> 00:40:12.800 align:middle line:84%
But in general, they are
disadvantageous to everything

00:40:12.800 --> 00:40:13.620 align:middle line:90%
we do.

00:40:13.620 --> 00:40:16.100 align:middle line:84%
And we live in a society
where we are never

00:40:16.100 --> 00:40:18.200 align:middle line:90%
reproached for doing too much.

00:40:18.200 --> 00:40:21.560 align:middle line:84%
But we are criticized
for not doing enough.

00:40:21.560 --> 00:40:25.400 align:middle line:84%
That's the price of screening,
accepting that sometimes we

00:40:25.400 --> 00:40:30.354 align:middle line:84%
will operate on woman
who didn't need it.

00:40:30.354 --> 00:40:32.220 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:40:32.220 --> 00:40:35.755 align:middle line:84%
>> As a patient, how do we know
if we've been saved or operated

00:40:35.755 --> 00:40:36.555 align:middle line:90%
on for nothing?

00:40:36.555 --> 00:40:44.630 align:middle line:90%


00:40:44.630 --> 00:40:49.570 align:middle line:84%
Marlo is a small town
to the west of London.

00:40:49.570 --> 00:40:52.060 align:middle line:90%
This question haunts Miriam.

00:40:52.060 --> 00:40:55.360 align:middle line:84%
A professor of philosophy,
she has just finished her PhD

00:40:55.360 --> 00:40:58.300 align:middle line:84%
on rationality and ethics,
a subject very close

00:40:58.300 --> 00:40:59.350 align:middle line:90%
to her heart.

00:40:59.350 --> 00:41:02.050 align:middle line:90%
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:41:02.050 --> 00:41:04.540 align:middle line:84%
>> 10 years ago, when she
underwent her very first

00:41:04.540 --> 00:41:07.810 align:middle line:84%
screening, they discovered,
as with Monique and Patricia,

00:41:07.810 --> 00:41:08.965 align:middle line:90%
precancerous lesions.

00:41:08.965 --> 00:41:13.600 align:middle line:90%


00:41:13.600 --> 00:41:17.230 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, I was completely
shocked, completely shocked.

00:41:17.230 --> 00:41:18.820 align:middle line:90%
Because I was healthy.

00:41:18.820 --> 00:41:20.230 align:middle line:90%
I was well.

00:41:20.230 --> 00:41:21.420 align:middle line:90%
I was looking forward--

00:41:21.420 --> 00:41:23.410 align:middle line:84%
I was just starting
teacher training.

00:41:23.410 --> 00:41:27.970 align:middle line:84%
At 50, I was looking
forward to a new career.

00:41:27.970 --> 00:41:31.150 align:middle line:90%
My kids were just growing.

00:41:31.150 --> 00:41:34.600 align:middle line:84%
My youngest son had just
started secondary school.

00:41:34.600 --> 00:41:36.110 align:middle line:90%
And life was fine.

00:41:36.110 --> 00:41:42.550 align:middle line:84%
And then I was told it might
be just coming to an end.

00:41:42.550 --> 00:41:46.240 align:middle line:84%
>> Back then despite her
doubts, after two consultations,

00:41:46.240 --> 00:41:50.870 align:middle line:84%
Miriam followed the course of
treatment her doctors advised.

00:41:50.870 --> 00:41:54.170 align:middle line:84%
>> They made it seem
like an emergency.

00:41:54.170 --> 00:41:56.300 align:middle line:90%
I was really put under pressure.

00:41:56.300 --> 00:41:57.560 align:middle line:90%
They wanted results.

00:41:57.560 --> 00:42:00.680 align:middle line:90%
They wanted decision.

00:42:00.680 --> 00:42:04.070 align:middle line:84%
I knew I wasn't going to get
any more of that doctor's time.

00:42:04.070 --> 00:42:06.830 align:middle line:84%
And you're conscious
of other people

00:42:06.830 --> 00:42:11.450 align:middle line:84%
with life threatening diagnoses
needing his attention.

00:42:11.450 --> 00:42:13.590 align:middle line:84%
You just think, I can't
take anymore of his time.

00:42:13.590 --> 00:42:18.930 align:middle line:90%


00:42:18.930 --> 00:42:21.890 align:middle line:84%
So you're put under
this pressure.

00:42:21.890 --> 00:42:23.460 align:middle line:90%
But there's no need.

00:42:23.460 --> 00:42:26.030 align:middle line:84%
I could have gone away and
said, well, I'll think about it.

00:42:26.030 --> 00:42:26.830 align:middle line:90%
I'll read about it.

00:42:26.830 --> 00:42:31.690 align:middle line:90%


00:42:31.690 --> 00:42:37.090 align:middle line:84%
It's when it's all over,
you start to evaluate.

00:42:37.090 --> 00:42:40.410 align:middle line:90%
You start to assess.

00:42:40.410 --> 00:42:43.390 align:middle line:84%
>> The operation was more
complex than planned.

00:42:43.390 --> 00:42:45.060 align:middle line:84%
And Miriam lost
her entire breast.

00:42:45.060 --> 00:42:48.360 align:middle line:90%


00:42:48.360 --> 00:42:51.480 align:middle line:84%
>> They actually remove
a part of your body.

00:42:51.480 --> 00:42:53.130 align:middle line:90%
It is an amputation.

00:42:53.130 --> 00:42:55.080 align:middle line:90%
It is so shocking.

00:42:55.080 --> 00:42:56.100 align:middle line:90%
It is so shocking.

00:42:56.100 --> 00:43:02.430 align:middle line:84%
I identified with soldiers
coming back from the war.

00:43:02.430 --> 00:43:03.960 align:middle line:90%
And it wasn't treated like that.

00:43:03.960 --> 00:43:08.040 align:middle line:84%
It was treated like going
to the dentist or something.

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:10.860 align:middle line:84%
They just process you
through-- nothing, nothing.

00:43:10.860 --> 00:43:15.000 align:middle line:90%
You're not supposed to care.

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:16.460 align:middle line:90%
And I did care.

00:43:16.460 --> 00:43:21.840 align:middle line:90%


00:43:21.840 --> 00:43:25.200 align:middle line:84%
>> Today, she has grave doubts
about her own experiences

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:28.080 align:middle line:84%
and is trying to raise
awareness to help other women.

00:43:28.080 --> 00:43:33.700 align:middle line:90%


00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:36.830 align:middle line:84%
>> I may or may not
have had my life saved.

00:43:36.830 --> 00:43:40.760 align:middle line:84%
I may or may not have needed
any of the treatment I had.

00:43:40.760 --> 00:43:43.010 align:middle line:90%
I have no way of knowing.

00:43:43.010 --> 00:43:46.250 align:middle line:84%
And nobody had thought
fit to mention this to me.

00:43:46.250 --> 00:43:49.090 align:middle line:84%
People seem to think that
I'm talking about me here.

00:43:49.090 --> 00:43:53.820 align:middle line:84%
And I'm saying, in my case,
it's unlikely that I benefited.

00:43:53.820 --> 00:43:55.530 align:middle line:90%
But other women have benefited.

00:43:55.530 --> 00:43:56.330 align:middle line:90%
No, no, no.

00:43:56.330 --> 00:43:57.300 align:middle line:90%
This is not true.

00:43:57.300 --> 00:43:58.430 align:middle line:90%
You cannot know.

00:43:58.430 --> 00:44:00.030 align:middle line:90%
No individual can know.

00:44:00.030 --> 00:44:03.440 align:middle line:90%


00:44:03.440 --> 00:44:07.760 align:middle line:84%
I feel betrayed by
those individuals,

00:44:07.760 --> 00:44:10.190 align:middle line:84%
every single person
who spoke to me

00:44:10.190 --> 00:44:13.370 align:middle line:84%
and failed to tell
me what they knew.

00:44:13.370 --> 00:44:16.040 align:middle line:90%


00:44:16.040 --> 00:44:18.636 align:middle line:90%
They betrayed me.

00:44:18.636 --> 00:44:22.080 align:middle line:90%
[WIND BLOWING]

00:44:22.080 --> 00:44:24.660 align:middle line:84%
>> What if breast cancer
screening does more harm than

00:44:24.660 --> 00:44:27.340 align:middle line:90%
good?

00:44:27.340 --> 00:44:30.490 align:middle line:84%
One man is today convinced
of this, having closely

00:44:30.490 --> 00:44:32.970 align:middle line:90%
analyzed all the data.

00:44:32.970 --> 00:44:35.920 align:middle line:84%
In 2000, Peter
Gotzsche, the leader

00:44:35.920 --> 00:44:39.370 align:middle line:84%
of the independent
Nordic Cochrane Center

00:44:39.370 --> 00:44:40.990 align:middle line:84%
was asked by the
Danish government

00:44:40.990 --> 00:44:42.190 align:middle line:90%
to consider this question.

00:44:42.190 --> 00:44:45.000 align:middle line:90%


00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.790 align:middle line:84%
>> I was asked by the Danish
National board of health

00:44:47.790 --> 00:44:51.330 align:middle line:90%
to review the screening trials.

00:44:51.330 --> 00:44:54.870 align:middle line:84%
Five weeks later,
there would be votings

00:44:54.870 --> 00:44:57.240 align:middle line:84%
in the Danish parliament
whether we should have

00:44:57.240 --> 00:44:59.400 align:middle line:90%
screening in the whole country.

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:03.600 align:middle line:84%
And we concluded
that we could not

00:45:03.600 --> 00:45:06.690 align:middle line:84%
exclude the possibility that
mammography screening might

00:45:06.690 --> 00:45:09.390 align:middle line:90%
do more harm than good.

00:45:09.390 --> 00:45:13.260 align:middle line:84%
This report never made it from
the National Board of Health

00:45:13.260 --> 00:45:16.230 align:middle line:90%
to the Minister of Health.

00:45:16.230 --> 00:45:17.820 align:middle line:84%
So he didn't know
about the report

00:45:17.820 --> 00:45:20.520 align:middle line:90%
on the day of the votings.

00:45:20.520 --> 00:45:25.160 align:middle line:90%
So something dirty was going on.

00:45:25.160 --> 00:45:27.500 align:middle line:84%
>> Stung into action,
Peter Gotzsche,

00:45:27.500 --> 00:45:30.230 align:middle line:84%
a biologist and specialist
in internal medicine

00:45:30.230 --> 00:45:34.280 align:middle line:84%
and statistics, persisted,
raising the alarm.

00:45:34.280 --> 00:45:37.760 align:middle line:84%
His studies were published in
two prestigious publications,

00:45:37.760 --> 00:45:40.970 align:middle line:84%
"The Lancet" and "The New
England Journal of Medicine."

00:45:40.970 --> 00:45:42.830 align:middle line:90%
They caused a sensation.

00:45:42.830 --> 00:45:46.880 align:middle line:84%
"The New York Times" and "Le
Monde" ran front page stories.

00:45:46.880 --> 00:45:50.600 align:middle line:84%
For the first time, someone had
examined the harmful effects

00:45:50.600 --> 00:45:51.680 align:middle line:90%
of overdiagnosis.

00:45:51.680 --> 00:45:54.760 align:middle line:90%


00:45:54.760 --> 00:45:56.470 align:middle line:90%
>> Overdiagnosed cancers?

00:45:56.470 --> 00:45:59.230 align:middle line:84%
They would never have been
found without screening.

00:45:59.230 --> 00:46:01.460 align:middle line:90%
So these women are healthy.

00:46:01.460 --> 00:46:05.770 align:middle line:84%
And when you treat healthy women
with radiotherapy, for example,

00:46:05.770 --> 00:46:07.720 align:middle line:90%
then you kill some of them.

00:46:07.720 --> 00:46:09.970 align:middle line:84%
Because they develop
heart disease or lung

00:46:09.970 --> 00:46:12.680 align:middle line:90%
cancer or other cancers.

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:17.740 align:middle line:84%
And these additional deaths
in healthy women amount

00:46:17.740 --> 00:46:23.230 align:middle line:84%
to at least as many deaths
as what mammography screening

00:46:23.230 --> 00:46:27.340 align:middle line:84%
can prevent in terms of
breast cancer deaths.

00:46:27.340 --> 00:46:31.570 align:middle line:84%
So it's clear to me that there
is absolutely no survival

00:46:31.570 --> 00:46:34.000 align:middle line:90%
benefit by going to screening.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:37.950 align:middle line:84%
Screening is
unequivocally harmful.

00:46:37.950 --> 00:46:39.340 align:middle line:90%
There's no survival benefit.

00:46:39.340 --> 00:46:40.140 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't exist.

00:46:40.140 --> 00:46:42.990 align:middle line:90%


00:46:42.990 --> 00:46:46.890 align:middle line:84%
>> Peter Gotzsche had reanalyzed
the initial studies in detail,

00:46:46.890 --> 00:46:51.120 align:middle line:84%
the ones carried out during the
1970s which predicted 30% more

00:46:51.120 --> 00:46:53.440 align:middle line:84%
deaths from breast
cancer amongst women who

00:46:53.440 --> 00:46:54.240 align:middle line:90%
weren't screened.

00:46:54.240 --> 00:46:59.200 align:middle line:90%


00:46:59.200 --> 00:47:01.280 align:middle line:84%
And according to
Gotzsche, these studies

00:47:01.280 --> 00:47:03.140 align:middle line:90%
contained irregularities.

00:47:03.140 --> 00:47:09.670 align:middle line:90%


00:47:09.670 --> 00:47:12.030 align:middle line:84%
The first was that certain
women were excluded

00:47:12.030 --> 00:47:14.550 align:middle line:84%
from the group that underwent
screening because they

00:47:14.550 --> 00:47:17.340 align:middle line:90%
had a history of breast cancer.

00:47:17.340 --> 00:47:19.830 align:middle line:84%
But no such exclusion
was made among the group

00:47:19.830 --> 00:47:21.990 align:middle line:90%
that did not undergo screening.

00:47:21.990 --> 00:47:24.480 align:middle line:84%
Naturally, this would
increase the mortality rate.

00:47:24.480 --> 00:47:29.360 align:middle line:90%


00:47:29.360 --> 00:47:31.180 align:middle line:84%
The second was that
the causes of death

00:47:31.180 --> 00:47:33.880 align:middle line:84%
were sometimes
difficult to determine.

00:47:33.880 --> 00:47:36.070 align:middle line:84%
Among the group that
was not screened,

00:47:36.070 --> 00:47:38.080 align:middle line:84%
deaths where the
cause was uncertain

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:40.180 align:middle line:84%
were attributed
to breast cancer,

00:47:40.180 --> 00:47:42.900 align:middle line:84%
again, increasing the breast
cancer mortality rate.

00:47:42.900 --> 00:47:46.900 align:middle line:90%


00:47:46.900 --> 00:47:50.140 align:middle line:84%
And thirdly, in the study that
was the most favorable in terms

00:47:50.140 --> 00:47:52.600 align:middle line:84%
of screening, the man
running the trials

00:47:52.600 --> 00:47:55.320 align:middle line:84%
owned a private company
involved in mammograms.

00:47:55.320 --> 00:48:00.880 align:middle line:90%


00:48:00.880 --> 00:48:03.520 align:middle line:84%
And all public breast
cancer screening programs

00:48:03.520 --> 00:48:06.040 align:middle line:84%
were set up because of a
belief in those studies.

00:48:06.040 --> 00:48:11.810 align:middle line:90%


00:48:11.810 --> 00:48:15.260 align:middle line:84%
>> There are huge financial
interests in mammography

00:48:15.260 --> 00:48:16.550 align:middle line:90%
screening.

00:48:16.550 --> 00:48:21.170 align:middle line:84%
In the United States, it's
a billion dollar business.

00:48:21.170 --> 00:48:24.410 align:middle line:84%
And also, in many
countries, you have

00:48:24.410 --> 00:48:26.870 align:middle line:84%
national mammography
screening programs

00:48:26.870 --> 00:48:29.280 align:middle line:90%
organized by the state.

00:48:29.280 --> 00:48:32.130 align:middle line:84%
And it's always
very, very difficult

00:48:32.130 --> 00:48:35.970 align:middle line:84%
to stop national
health programs.

00:48:35.970 --> 00:48:38.580 align:middle line:84%
Because in order to stop
them, you have to admit,

00:48:38.580 --> 00:48:41.400 align:middle line:90%
as a politician, we were wrong.

00:48:41.400 --> 00:48:44.230 align:middle line:84%
Politicians rarely admit
that they did anything wrong.

00:48:44.230 --> 00:48:46.760 align:middle line:90%


00:48:46.760 --> 00:48:49.160 align:middle line:84%
>> We contacted the
French Ministry of Health.

00:48:49.160 --> 00:48:52.310 align:middle line:84%
But they couldn't find
the time to respond.

00:48:52.310 --> 00:48:54.830 align:middle line:84%
But what do they think about
it at the High Authority

00:48:54.830 --> 00:48:57.620 align:middle line:84%
of Health, the body
charged with evaluating

00:48:57.620 --> 00:49:02.350 align:middle line:84%
the benefits of public
health policy in France?

00:49:02.350 --> 00:49:05.690 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:49:05.690 --> 00:49:09.710 align:middle line:84%
>>INTERPRETER: For the moment,
France's health authorities

00:49:09.710 --> 00:49:12.860 align:middle line:84%
has a position that for
any medical intervention,

00:49:12.860 --> 00:49:14.270 align:middle line:90%
there are benefits and risks.

00:49:14.270 --> 00:49:17.270 align:middle line:84%
And those benefits
should outweigh the risk.

00:49:17.270 --> 00:49:18.980 align:middle line:84%
In general, breast
cancer screening

00:49:18.980 --> 00:49:22.130 align:middle line:84%
reduces the mortality
rates by around 20%.

00:49:22.130 --> 00:49:27.170 align:middle line:90%


00:49:27.170 --> 00:49:29.510 align:middle line:84%
It's a tricky and
emotional subject.

00:49:29.510 --> 00:49:32.960 align:middle line:84%
I'm not sure that, if you ask
me again in five years' time,

00:49:32.960 --> 00:49:36.890 align:middle line:84%
I'd say the same thing
as I'm saying today.

00:49:36.890 --> 00:49:39.800 align:middle line:84%
>> Especially given that breast
cancer screening has yet to be

00:49:39.800 --> 00:49:42.970 align:middle line:90%
fully understood.

00:49:42.970 --> 00:49:45.420 align:middle line:84%
In Birmingham in
the UK, one doctor

00:49:45.420 --> 00:49:47.970 align:middle line:84%
is carrying out some
unusual experiments

00:49:47.970 --> 00:49:51.640 align:middle line:84%
that may revolutionize
medical practices.

00:49:51.640 --> 00:49:53.920 align:middle line:84%
He believes that
precancerous lesions,

00:49:53.920 --> 00:49:57.220 align:middle line:84%
or carcinomas in situ,
detected by chance,

00:49:57.220 --> 00:49:58.890 align:middle line:84%
should not be
systematically removed.

00:49:58.890 --> 00:50:03.940 align:middle line:90%


00:50:03.940 --> 00:50:06.490 align:middle line:84%
>> Ductal carcinoma in
situ is not one disease.

00:50:06.490 --> 00:50:08.150 align:middle line:90%
It's a spectrum of diseases.

00:50:08.150 --> 00:50:10.930 align:middle line:84%
And we call them low,
intermediate, or high grade

00:50:10.930 --> 00:50:12.412 align:middle line:90%
DCIS.

00:50:12.412 --> 00:50:13.870 align:middle line:84%
And we're interested
in finding out

00:50:13.870 --> 00:50:18.190 align:middle line:84%
whether low, or some of the
intermediate grade DCIS,

00:50:18.190 --> 00:50:22.030 align:middle line:84%
really need to have
surgical treatment or not.

00:50:22.030 --> 00:50:24.640 align:middle line:84%
So then, the patients
will be randomized

00:50:24.640 --> 00:50:27.960 align:middle line:84%
to either have surgery
as they would normally--

00:50:27.960 --> 00:50:31.230 align:middle line:84%
so half the patients go through
the normal treatment pathway.

00:50:31.230 --> 00:50:33.970 align:middle line:84%
But half the patients,
instead of going immediately

00:50:33.970 --> 00:50:38.770 align:middle line:84%
to surgery, would be observed
with mammograms performed

00:50:38.770 --> 00:50:40.870 align:middle line:90%
every year for 10 years.

00:50:40.870 --> 00:50:43.600 align:middle line:84%
But I would be very surprised
to find that there's a survival

00:50:43.600 --> 00:50:44.400 align:middle line:90%
difference.

00:50:44.400 --> 00:50:47.075 align:middle line:84%
I think it's a very safe
trial for patients to go into.

00:50:47.075 --> 00:50:48.700 align:middle line:84%
And that what we end
up doing is seeing

00:50:48.700 --> 00:50:51.790 align:middle line:84%
that patients can delay
their surgery safely

00:50:51.790 --> 00:50:54.085 align:middle line:84%
without any detriment to
their overall survival.

00:50:54.085 --> 00:50:58.840 align:middle line:90%


00:50:58.840 --> 00:51:03.604 align:middle line:84%
>> The first results will be
available in 15 years' time.

00:51:03.604 --> 00:51:06.640 align:middle line:90%
>> [SPEAKING FRENCH].

00:51:06.640 --> 00:51:09.280 align:middle line:84%
>> Meanwhile, Ghislaine
will continue to enjoy her

00:51:09.280 --> 00:51:11.470 align:middle line:84%
grandchildren between
her screenings.

00:51:11.470 --> 00:51:14.180 align:middle line:90%


00:51:14.180 --> 00:51:17.630 align:middle line:84%
Monique eventually had a second
operation on the same breast

00:51:17.630 --> 00:51:21.290 align:middle line:90%
and 35 radiotherapy sessions.

00:51:21.290 --> 00:51:23.000 align:middle line:84%
Nobody can say
whether or not she

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:26.270 align:middle line:84%
was saved by her screening
and subsequent operations,

00:51:26.270 --> 00:51:30.140 align:middle line:90%
but she feels reassured.

00:51:30.140 --> 00:51:31.910 align:middle line:84%
Miriam will never
know if she was

00:51:31.910 --> 00:51:34.250 align:middle line:90%
the victim of overdiagnosis.

00:51:34.250 --> 00:51:36.470 align:middle line:84%
But she continues her
fight to provide women

00:51:36.470 --> 00:51:39.605 align:middle line:84%
with better information so
they can make informed choices.

00:51:39.605 --> 00:51:43.160 align:middle line:90%


00:51:43.160 --> 00:51:46.730 align:middle line:84%
Patricia is preparing to
set sail again on her boat.

00:51:46.730 --> 00:51:49.280 align:middle line:84%
After scientific
studies and biopsies,

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:51.950 align:middle line:84%
she is reassured that
her precancerous lesions

00:51:51.950 --> 00:51:55.340 align:middle line:90%
have disappeared.

00:51:55.340 --> 00:51:58.580 align:middle line:84%
Four individual stories
that reveal the complexity

00:51:58.580 --> 00:52:00.920 align:middle line:84%
of a breast cancer
screening policy

00:52:00.920 --> 00:52:03.200 align:middle line:84%
that creates more
doubt than certitude.

00:52:03.200 --> 00:52:09.200 align:middle line:90%


00:52:09.200 --> 00:52:11.950 align:middle line:90%
[WATER LAPPING]

00:52:11.950 --> 00:52:33.000 align:middle line:90%